The Africa Airspace Programme (AAP) is a public-private partnership between the African Union Commission, the African Civil Aviation Commission (ACAC) and the European Union. It was launched on 28 November 2016 in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia with the purpose of improving air transport in Africa by harmonising airspace and reducing air navigation costs for the continent's citizens. The programme aims to modernise the continent's airspace management through the implementation of cost-effective and efficient procedures, while also establishing an African Air Transport Indaba aimed at creating a platform for discussion among all stakeholders to find solutions to address existing issues and propose concrete actions to improve air transport in Africa.
The first phase of the AAP will focus on:
developing a Regulatory Implementation Strategy that outlines the steps required to implement the necessary regulatory changes for the realisation of the Single African Air Transport Market (SAATM). This strategy identifies the key constraints and challenges, defines policy options and provides a timeline for action;
developing an Action Plan for implementing the Single African Air Transport Market (SAATM), including the associated costs and financing needs of the SAATM initiative over the next ten years;
establishing an African Air Transport Indaba as a platform for discussions among key stakeholders to address existing issues and propose concrete actions to improve air transport in Africa;
updating the Continental Framework for the establishment of the African Air Transport Indaba;
establishing a Coordination Unit to support the implementation of the activities of the AAP.
